# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kinetic-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The **Boltzmann equation** or **Boltzmann transport equation** (**BTE**) describes the statistical behaviour of a thermodynamic system not in a state of equilibrium; it was devised by Ludwig Boltzmann in 1872.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The classic example of such a system is a fluid with temperature gradients in space causing heat to flow from hotter regions to colder ones, by the random but biased transport of the particles making up that fluid.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In the modern literature the term Boltzmann equation is often used in a more general sense, referring to any kinetic equation that describes the change of a macroscopic quantity in a thermodynamic system, such as energy, charge or particle number.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation can be used to determine how physical quantities change, such as heat energy and momentum, when a fluid is in transport.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] One may also derive other properties characteristic to fluids such as viscosity, thermal conductivity, and electrical conductivity (by treating the charge carriers in a material as a gas).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The equation is a nonlinear integro-differential equation, and the unknown function in the equation is a probability density function in six-dimensional space of a particle position and momentum.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The problem of existence and uniqueness of solutions is still not fully resolved, but some recent results are quite promising.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The set of all possible positions **r** and momenta **p** is called the phase space of the system; in other words a set of three coordinates for each position coordinate *x, y, z*, and three more for each momentum component *px*, *py*, *pz*.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The entire space is 6-dimensional: a point in this space is (**r**, **p**) = (*x, y, z, px, py, pz*), and each coordinate is parameterized by time *t*.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] While *f* is associated with a number of particles, the phase space is for one-particle (not all of them, which is usually the case with deterministic many-body systems), since only one **r** and **p** is in question.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] It is assumed the particles in the system are identical (so each has an identical mass m).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] For a mixture of more than one chemical species, one distribution is needed for each, see below.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] where the "force" term corresponds to the forces exerted on the particles by an external influence (not by the particles themselves), the "diff" term represents the diffusion of particles, and "coll" is the collision term – accounting for the forces acting between particles in collisions.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Expressions for each term on the right side are provided below.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Note that some authors use the particle velocity **v** instead of momentum **p**; they are related in the definition of momentum by **p** = *m***v**.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Consider particles described by *f*, each experiencing an *external* force **F** not due to other particles (see the collision term for the latter treatment).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Suppose at time t some number of particles all have position **r** within element $d^{3}\mathbf {r}$ and momentum **p** within $d^{3}\mathbf {p}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] If a force **F** instantly acts on each particle, then at time *t* + Δ*t* their position will be $\mathbf {r} +\Delta \mathbf {r} =\mathbf {r} +{\frac {\mathbf {p} }{m}}\,\Delta t$ and momentum $\mathbf {p} +\Delta \mathbf {p} =\mathbf {p} +\mathbf {F} \Delta t$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Note that we have used the fact that the phase space volume element $d^{3}\mathbf {r} \,d^{3}\mathbf {p}$ is constant, which can be shown using Hamilton's equations (see the discussion under Liouville's theorem).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] where Δ*f* is the *total* change in *f*.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In this context, **F**(**r**, *t*) is the force field acting on the particles in the fluid, and m is the mass of the particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The term on the right hand side is added to describe the effect of collisions between particles; if it is zero then the particles do not collide.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The collisionless Boltzmann equation, where individual collisions are replaced with long-range aggregated interactions, e.g.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Coulomb interactions, is often called the Vlasov equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This equation is more useful than the principal one above, yet still incomplete, since *f* cannot be solved unless the collision term in *f* is known.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This term cannot be found as easily or generally as the others – it is a statistical term representing the particle collisions, and requires knowledge of the statistics the particles obey, like the Maxwell–Boltzmann, Fermi–Dirac or Bose–Einstein distributions.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] A key insight applied by Boltzmann was to determine the collision term resulting solely from two-body collisions between particles that are assumed to be uncorrelated prior to the collision.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This assumption was referred to by Boltzmann as the "*Stosszahlansatz*" and is also known as the "molecular chaos assumption".
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Since much of the challenge in solving the Boltzmann equation originates with the complex collision term, attempts have been made to "model" and simplify the collision term.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The best known model equation is due to Bhatnagar, Gross and Krook.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] where $\nu$ is the molecular collision frequency, and $f_{0}$ is the local Maxwellian distribution function given the gas temperature at this point in space.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This is also called "relaxation time approximation".
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] and *Iij* is the differential cross-section, as before, between particles *i* and *j*.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The integration is over the momentum components in the integrand (which are labelled *i* and *j*).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The sum of integrals describes the entry and exit of particles of species *i* in or out of the phase-space element.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation can be used to derive the fluid dynamic conservation laws for mass, charge, momentum, and energy.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Since the conservation equations involve tensors, the Einstein summation convention will be used where repeated indices in a product indicate summation over those indices.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Thus $\mathbf {x} \mapsto x_{i}$ and $\mathbf {p} \mapsto p_{i}=mv_{i}$ , where $v_{i}$ is the particle velocity vector.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Define $A(p_{i})$ as some function of momentum $p_{i}$ only, whose total value is conserved in a collision.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Assume also that the force $F_{i}$ is a function of position only, and that *f* is zero for $p_{i}\to \pm \infty$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] where the last term is zero, since *A* is conserved in a collision.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The values of *A* correspond to moments of velocity $v_{i}$ (and momentum $p_{i}$ , as they are linearly dependent).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] where $P_{ij}=\rho \langle (v_{i}-V_{i})(v_{j}-V_{j})\rangle$ is the pressure tensor (the viscous stress tensor plus the hydrostatic pressure).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] It is possible to write down relativistic quantum Boltzmann equations for relativistic quantum systems in which the number of particles is not conserved in collisions.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This has several applications in physical cosmology, including the formation of the light elements in Big Bang nucleosynthesis, the production of dark matter and baryogenesis.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] It is not a priori clear that the state of a quantum system can be characterized by a classical phase space density *f*.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] However, for a wide class of applications a well-defined generalization of *f* exists which is the solution of an effective Boltzmann equation that can be derived from first principles of quantum field theory.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation is of use in galactic dynamics.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In physical cosmology the fully covariant approach has been used to study the cosmic microwave background radiation.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] More generically the study of processes in the early universe often attempt to take into account the effects of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In the very dense medium formed by the primordial plasma after the Big Bang, particles are continuously created and annihilated.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In such an environment quantum coherence and the spatial extension of the wavefunction can affect the dynamics, making it questionable whether the classical phase space distribution *f* that appears in the Boltzmann equation is suitable to describe the system.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In many cases it is, however, possible to derive an effective Boltzmann equation for a generalized distribution function from first principles of quantum field theory.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This includes the formation of the light elements in Big Bang nucleosynthesis, the production of dark matter and baryogenesis.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Exact solutions to the Boltzmann equations have been proven to exist in some cases; this analytical approach provides insight, but is not generally usable in practical problems.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Assuming a specific inverse power law between interacting particles, fully closed-form solutions to boundary value problems involving gross, spatially homogenous rates of deformation can be found and studied analytically.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Instead, numerical methods (including finite elements and lattice Boltzmann methods) are generally used to find approximate solutions to the various forms of the Boltzmann equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Example applications range from hypersonic aerodynamics in rarefied gas flows to plasma flows.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] An application of the Boltzmann equation in electrodynamics is the calculation of the electrical conductivity - the result is in leading order identical with the semiclassical result.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Close to local equilibrium, solution of the Boltzmann equation can be represented by an asymptotic expansion in powers of Knudsen number (the Chapman–Enskog expansion).
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The first two terms of this expansion give the Euler equations and the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The problem of developing mathematically the limiting processes, which lead from the atomistic view (represented by Boltzmann's equation) to the laws of motion of continua, is an important part of Hilbert's sixth problem.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The Boltzmann equation is valid only under several assumptions.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] For instance, the particles are assumed to be pointlike, i.e. without having a finite size.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] There exists a generalization of the Boltzmann equation that is called the Enskog equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] The collision term is modified in Enskog equations such that particles have a finite size, for example they can be modelled as spheres having a fixed radius.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] No further degrees of freedom besides translational motion are assumed for the particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] If there are internal degrees of freedom, the Boltzmann equation has to be generalized and might possess inelastic collisions.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Many real fluids like liquids or dense gases have besides the features mentioned above more complex forms of collisions, there will be not only binary, but also ternary and higher order collisions.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] These must be derived by using the BBGKY hierarchy.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Boltzmann-like equations are also used for the movement of cells.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Since cells are composite particles that carry internal degrees of freedom, the corresponding generalized Boltzmann equations must have inelastic collision integrals.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] Such equations can describe invasions of cancer cells in tissue, morphogenesis, and chemotaxis-related effects.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] In 2024, Yu Deng, Zaher Hani, and Xiao Ma established a major extension of Lanford's theorem by proving that the Boltzmann equation can be rigorously derived from the Newtonian mechanics of a dilute gas of hard spheres for *practically unlimited time intervals*.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This result extends the 1975 breakthrough by Oscar Lanford, which was restricted to very short times, and provides a complete microscopic-to-mesoscopic derivation valid as long as the corresponding Boltzmann equation admits a classical solution.
[src:kinetic-theory/boltzmann-equation] This work addresses a key aspect of Hilbert's sixth problem by rigorously linking particle-level Newtonian dynamics with the mesoscopic kinetic description, and contributes to understanding how macroscopic irreversibility emerges from time-reversible microscopic laws.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] In physics and chemistry, **effusion** is the process in which a gas escapes from a container through a hole of diameter considerably smaller than the mean free path of the molecules.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Such a hole is often described as a *pinhole* and the escape of the gas is due to the pressure difference between the container and the exterior.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Under these conditions, essentially all molecules which arrive at the hole continue and pass through the hole, since collisions between molecules in the region of the hole are negligible.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Conversely, when the diameter is larger than the mean free path of the gas, flow obeys the Sampson flow law.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] In medical terminology, an **effusion** refers to accumulation of fluid in an anatomic space, usually without loculation.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Specific examples include subdural, mastoid, pericardial and pleural effusions.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] The word effusion derives from the Latin word, effundo, which means "shed", "pour forth", "pour out", "utter", "lavish", "waste".
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Effusion from an equilibrated container into outside vacuum can be calculated based on kinetic theory.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] An example is the recoil force on a balloon with a small hole flying in vacuum.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] where m is the mass of one molecule, $v_{\rm {rms}}$ is the root-mean-square speed of the molecules, and $k_{\rm {B}}$ is the Boltzmann constant.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Here $\Delta P$ is the gas pressure difference across the barrier, A is the area of the hole, $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, R is the gas constant and T is the absolute temperature.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] where $\Phi _{V}$ is the volumetric flow rate of the gas, $P_{\rm {avg}}$ is the average pressure on either side of the orifice, and d is the hole diameter.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] At constant pressure and temperature, the root-mean-square speed and therefore the effusion rate are inversely proportional to the square root of the molecular weight.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Gases with a lower molecular weight effuse more rapidly than gases with a higher molecular weight, so that the *number* of lighter molecules passing through the hole per unit time is greater.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Scottish chemist Thomas Graham (1805–1869) found experimentally that the rate of effusion of a gas is inversely proportional to the square root of the mass of its particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] In other words, the ratio of the rates of effusion of two gases at the same temperature and pressure is given by the inverse ratio of the square roots of the masses of the gas particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] where $M_{1}$ and $M_{2}$ represent the molar masses of the gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] This equation is known as Graham's law of effusion.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] The effusion rate for a gas depends directly on the average velocity of its particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Thus, the faster the gas particles are moving, the more likely they are to pass through the effusion orifice.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] The Knudsen cell is used to measure the vapor pressures of a solid with very low vapor pressure.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] Such a solid forms a vapor at low pressure by sublimation.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] The vapor slowly effuses through a pinhole, and the loss of mass is proportional to the vapor pressure and can be used to determine this pressure.
[src:kinetic-theory/effusion] The heat of sublimation can also be determined by measuring the vapor pressure as a function of temperature, using the Clausius–Clapeyron relation.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The **ideal gas law**, also called the **general gas equation**, is the equation of state of a hypothetical ideal gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] It is a good approximation of the behavior of many gases under many conditions, although it has several limitations.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] It was first stated by Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron and independently of him, Dmitry Mendeleev in 1834 as a combination of the empirical Boyle's law, Charles's law, Avogadro's law, and Gay-Lussac's law.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] $pV=nRT$ where p, V, and T are respectively the pressure, volume, and temperature, n is the amount of substance, and R is the ideal gas constant.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] It can also be derived from the microscopic kinetic theory, as was achieved (independently) by August Krönig in 1856 and Rudolf Clausius in 1857.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The state of an amount of gas is determined by its pressure, volume, and temperature.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The modern form of the equation relates these simply in two main forms.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The temperature used in the equation of state is an absolute temperature: the appropriate SI unit is the kelvin.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] In SI units, *p* is measured in pascals, *V* is measured in cubic meters, *n* is measured in moles, and *T* in kelvins (the Kelvin scale is a shifted Celsius scale, where 0 K = −273.15 °C, the lowest possible temperature).
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] How much gas is present could be specified by giving the mass instead of the chemical amount of gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Therefore, an alternative form of the ideal gas law may be useful.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] This form of the ideal gas law is very useful because it links pressure, density, and temperature in a unique formula independent of the quantity of the considered gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] It is common, especially in engineering and meteorological applications, to represent the **specific** gas constant by the symbol *R*.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] In such cases, the **universal** gas constant is usually given a different symbol such as ${\bar {R}}$ or $R^{*}$ to distinguish it.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] In any case, the context and/or units of the gas constant should make it clear as to whether the universal or specific gas constant is being used.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] In SI units, *p* is measured in pascals, *V* in cubic metres, *T* in kelvins, and *k*B = 1.38×10−23 J⋅K−1 in SI units.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Combining the laws of Charles, Boyle, and Gay-Lussac gives the **combined gas law**, which can take the same functional form as the ideal gas law.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where P is the pressure of the gas, V is the volume of the gas, T is the absolute temperature of the gas, and k is a constant.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] According to the assumptions of the kinetic theory of ideal gases, one can consider that there are no intermolecular attractions between the molecules, or atoms, of an ideal gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] In other words, its potential energy is zero.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Hence, all the energy possessed by the gas is the kinetic energy of the molecules, or atoms, of the gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] This corresponds to the kinetic energy of *n* moles of a monoatomic gas having 3 degrees of freedom: *x*, *y*, *z*.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The table here below gives this relationship for different amounts of a monoatomic gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The table below essentially simplifies the ideal gas equation for a particular process, making the equation easier to solve using numerical methods.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] A thermodynamic process is defined as a system that moves from state 1 to state 2, where the state number is denoted by a subscript.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] As shown in the first column of the table, basic thermodynamic processes are defined such that one of the gas properties (*P*, *V*, *T*, *S*, or *H*) is constant throughout the process.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] For a given thermodynamic process, in order to specify the extent of a particular process, one of the properties ratios (which are listed under the column labeled "known ratio") must be specified (either directly or indirectly).
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Also, the property for which the ratio is known must be distinct from the property held constant in the previous column (otherwise the ratio would be unity, and not enough information would be available to simplify the gas law equation).
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] In the final three columns, the properties (*p*, *V*, or *T*) at state 2 can be calculated from the properties at state 1 using the equations listed.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The equation of state given here (*PV* = *nRT*) applies only to an ideal gas, or as an approximation to a real gas that behaves sufficiently like an ideal gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] There are in fact many different forms of the equation of state.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Since the ideal gas law neglects both molecular size and intermolecular attractions, it is most accurate for monatomic gases at high temperatures and low pressures.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The molecular size becomes less important for lower densities, i.e. for larger volumes at lower pressures, because the average distance between adjacent molecules becomes much larger than the molecular size.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The relative importance of intermolecular attractions diminishes with increasing thermal kinetic energy, i.e., with increasing temperatures.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] More detailed *equations of state*, such as the van der Waals equation, account for deviations from ideality caused by molecular size and intermolecular forces.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The empirical laws that led to the derivation of the ideal gas law were discovered with experiments that changed only 2 state variables of the gas and kept every other one constant.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where *P* stands for pressure, *V* for volume, *N* for number of particles in the gas and *T* for temperature; where $C_{1},C_{2},C_{3},C_{4},C_{5},C_{6}$ are constants in this context because of each equation requiring only the parameters explicitly noted in them changing.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] To derive the ideal gas law one does not need to know all 6 formulas, one can just know 3 and with those derive the rest or just one more to be able to get the ideal gas law, which needs 4.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Since each formula only holds when only the state variables involved in said formula change while the others (which are a property of the gas but are not explicitly noted in said formula) remain constant, we cannot simply use algebra and directly combine them all.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] This is why: Boyle did his experiments while keeping *N* and *T* constant and this must be taken into account (in this same way, every experiment kept some parameter as constant and this must be taken into account for the derivation).
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Keeping this in mind, to carry the derivation on correctly, one must imagine the gas being altered by one process at a time (as it was done in the experiments).
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Another equivalent result, using the fact that $nR=Nk_{\text{B}}$ , where *n* is the number of moles in the gas and *R* is the universal gas constant, is: $PV=nRT,$ which is known as the ideal gas law.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] If three of the six equations are known, it may be possible to derive the remaining three using the same method.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] However, because each formula has two variables, this is possible only for certain groups of three.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] For example, if you were to have equations (**1**), (**2**) and (**4**) you would not be able to get any more because combining any two of them will only give you the third.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where the numbers represent the gas laws numbered above.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] If you were to use the same method used above on 2 of the 3 laws on the vertices of one triangle that has a "O" inside it, you would get the third.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Consider a container in the $xyz$ Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] For simplicity, we assume that a third of the molecules moves parallel to the x -axis, a third moves parallel to the y -axis and a third moves parallel to the z -axis.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] If all molecules move with the same velocity v , denote the corresponding pressure by $P_{0}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] We choose an area S on a wall of the container, perpendicular to the x -axis.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] When time t elapses, all molecules in the volume $vtS$ moving in the positive direction of the x -axis will hit the area.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] There are $NvtS$ molecules in a part of volume $vtS$ of the container, but only one sixth (i.e. a half of a third) of them moves in the positive direction of the x -axis.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Therefore, the number of molecules $N'$ that will hit the area S when the time t elapses is $NvtS/6$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] When a molecule bounces off the wall of the container, it changes its momentum $\mathbf {p} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {p} _{2}=-\mathbf {p} _{1}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Hence the magnitude of change of the momentum of one molecule is $|\mathbf {p} _{2}-\mathbf {p} _{1}|=2mv$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The magnitude of the change of momentum of all molecules that bounce off the area S when time t elapses is then $|\Delta \mathbf {p} |=2mvN'/V=NtSmv^{2}/(3V)=ntSmv^{2}/3$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] We considered a situation where all molecules move with the same velocity v .
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Let **q** = (*q*x, *q*y, *q*z) and **p** = (*p*x, *p*y, *p*z) denote the position vector and momentum vector of a particle of an ideal gas, respectively.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Let **F** denote the net force on that particle.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where the first equality is Newton's second law, and the second line uses Hamilton's equations and the equipartition theorem.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] By Newton's third law and the ideal gas assumption, the net force of the system is the force applied by the walls of the container, and this force is given by the pressure *P* of the gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where d**S** is the infinitesimal area element along the walls of the container.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where *dV* is an infinitesimal volume within the container and *V* is the total volume of the container.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where *n* = *N*/*N*A is the number of moles of gas and *R* = *N*A*k*B is the gas constant.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] An additional derivation is possible using the particle in a box model of quantum mechanics.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where $n_{x}$ , $n_{y}$ and $n_{z}$ are the quantum numbers for translational motion in the three base directions, $E_{x}$ , $E_{y}$ and $E_{z}$ are the kinetic energies associated with translational motion in these directions.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] Analogs of this derivation for cylindrical and spherical boxes give the same result.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] where $L^{d}$ is the extent of the *d*-dimensional domain in which the gas exists.
[src:kinetic-theory/ideal-gas-law] The quantity dimension of the pressure-like quantity $P^{(d)}$ changes with the space dimensionality *d*: it corresponds to a force per length (for *d*=1), force per area (*d*=2), or force per volume (*d*=3).
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The **kinetic theory of gases** is a simple classical model of the thermodynamic behavior of gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Its introduction allowed many principal concepts of thermodynamics to be established.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] It treats a gas as composed of numerous particles, too small to be seen with a microscope, in constant, random motion.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] These particles are now known to be the atoms or molecules of the gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The basic version of the model describes an ideal gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] It treats the collisions as perfectly elastic and as the only interaction between the particles, which are additionally assumed to be much smaller than their average distance apart.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Due to the time reversibility of microscopic dynamics (microscopic reversibility), the kinetic theory is also connected to the principle of detailed balance, in terms of the fluctuation-dissipation theorem (for Brownian motion) and the Onsager reciprocal relations.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The theory was historically significant as the first explicit exercise of the ideas of statistical mechanics and it forms the theoretical foundation for rarefied gas dynamics.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In about 50 BCE, the Roman philosopher Lucretius proposed that apparently static macroscopic bodies were composed on a small scale of rapidly moving atoms all bouncing off each other.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This Epicurean atomistic point of view was rarely considered in the subsequent centuries, when Aristotelian ideas were dominant.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] One of the first and boldest statements on the relationship between motion of particles and heat was by the English philosopher Francis Bacon in 1620.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Boyle also believed that all macroscopic properties, including color, taste and elasticity, are caused by and ultimately consist of nothing but the arrangement and motion of indivisible particles of matter.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In a lecture of 1681, Hooke asserted a direct relationship between the temperature of an object and the speed of its internal particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Also the transfer of heat was explained by the motion of particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1738 Daniel Bernoulli published *Hydrodynamica*, which laid the basis for the kinetic theory of gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In this work, Bernoulli posited the argument, that gases consist of great numbers of molecules moving in all directions, that their impact on a surface causes the pressure of the gas, and that their average kinetic energy determines the temperature of the gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The theory was not immediately accepted, in part because conservation of energy had not yet been established, and it was not obvious to physicists how the collisions between molecules could be perfectly elastic.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Pioneers of the kinetic theory, whose work was also largely neglected by their contemporaries, were Mikhail Lomonosov (1747), Georges-Louis Le Sage (ca.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] 1780, published 1818), John Herapath (1816) and John James Waterston (1843), which connected their research with the development of mechanical explanations of gravitation.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1856 August Krönig created a simple gas-kinetic model, which only considered the translational motion of the particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1857 Rudolf Clausius developed a similar, but more sophisticated version of the theory, which included translational and, contrary to Krönig, also rotational and vibrational molecular motions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In this same work he introduced the concept of mean free path of a particle.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In 1859, after reading a paper about the diffusion of molecules by Clausius, Scottish physicist James Clerk Maxwell formulated the Maxwell distribution of molecular velocities, which gave the proportion of molecules having a certain velocity in a specific range.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This was the first-ever statistical law in physics.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Maxwell also gave the first mechanical argument that molecular collisions entail an equalization of temperatures and hence a tendency towards equilibrium.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The logarithmic connection between entropy and probability was also first stated by Boltzmann.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] At the beginning of the 20th century, atoms were considered by many physicists to be purely hypothetical constructs, rather than real objects.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] An important turning point was Albert Einstein's (1905) and Marian Smoluchowski's (1906) papers on Brownian motion, which succeeded in making certain accurate quantitative predictions based on the kinetic theory.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Following the development of the Boltzmann equation, a framework for its use in developing transport equations was developed independently by David Enskog and Sydney Chapman in 1917 and 1916.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The framework provided a route to prediction of the transport properties of dilute gases, and became known as Chapman–Enskog theory.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The framework was gradually expanded throughout the following century, eventually becoming a route to prediction of transport properties in real, dense gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Thus, the dynamics of particle motion can be treated classically, and the equations of motion are time-reversible.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] As a simplifying assumption, the particles are usually assumed to have the same mass as one another; however, the theory can be generalized to a mass distribution, with each mass type contributing to the gas properties independently of one another in agreement with Dalton's law of partial pressures.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Many of the model's predictions are the same whether or not collisions between particles are included, so they are often neglected as a simplifying assumption in derivations (see below).
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] More modern developments, such as the revised Enskog theory and the extended Bhatnagar–Gross–Krook model, relax one or more of the above assumptions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] While theories relaxing the assumptions that the gas particles occupy negligible volume and that collisions are strictly elastic have been successful, it has been shown that relaxing the requirement of interactions being binary and uncorrelated will eventually lead to divergent results.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In the kinetic theory of gases, the pressure is assumed to be equal to the force (per unit area) exerted by the individual gas atoms or molecules hitting and rebounding from the gas container's surface.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Consider a gas particle traveling at velocity, ${\textstyle v_{i}}$ , along the ${\hat {i}}$ -direction in an enclosed volume with characteristic length, $L_{i}$ , cross-sectional area, $A_{i}$ , and volume, $V=A_{i}L_{i}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Now consider a large number, N , of gas particles with random orientation in a three-dimensional volume.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This is an important, non-trivial result of the kinetic theory because it relates pressure, a macroscopic property, to the translational kinetic energy of the molecules, which is a microscopic property.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The mass density of a gas $\rho$ is expressed through the total mass of gas particles and through volume of this gas: $\rho ={\frac {Nm}{V}}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In the limit of small speeds, the expression becomes $P\approx \rho {\overline {v^{2}}}/3$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Equation (**3**) is one important result of the kinetic theory: *The average molecular kinetic energy is proportional to the ideal gas law's absolute temperature*.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Thus, the product of pressure and volume per mole is proportional to the average translational molecular kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The equipartition theorem requires that kinetic energy is partitioned equally between all kinetic degrees of freedom, *D*.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] A monatomic gas is axially symmetric about each spatial axis, so that *D* = 3 comprising translational motion along each axis.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] A diatomic gas is axially symmetric about only one axis, so that *D* = 5, comprising translational motion along three axes and rotational motion along two axes.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] A polyatomic gas, like water, is not radially symmetric about any axis, resulting in *D* = 6, comprising 3 translational and 3 rotational degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Therefore, the kinetic energy per kelvin of one mole of monatomic ideal gas (*D* = 3) is $K={\frac {D}{2}}k_{\text{B}}N_{\text{A}}={\frac {3}{2}}R,$ where $N_{\text{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, and *R* is the ideal gas constant.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] At higher temperatures (typically thousands of kelvins), vibrational modes become active to provide additional degrees of freedom, creating a temperature-dependence on *D* and the total molecular energy.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Quantum statistical mechanics is needed to accurately compute these contributions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Then for a small area $dA$ on the container wall, a particle with speed v at angle $\theta$ from the normal of the area $dA$ , will collide with the area within time interval $dt$ , if it is within the distance $v\,dt$ from the area $dA$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Therefore, all the particles with speed v at angle $\theta$ from the normal that can reach area $dA$ within time interval $dt$ are contained in the tilted pipe with a height of $v\cos(\theta )dt$ and a volume of $v\cos(\theta )\,dA\,dt$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This quantity is also known as the "impingement rate" in vacuum physics.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that to calculate the average speed ${\bar {v}}$ of the Maxwell's velocity distribution, one has to integrate over $v>0$ , $0<\theta <\pi$ , $0<\phi <2\pi$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The above expression is consistent with Graham's law.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The most probable (or mode) speed $v_{\text{p}}$ is 81.6% of the root-mean-square speed $v_{\text{rms}}$ , and the mean (arithmetic mean, or average) speed ${\bar {v}}$ is 92.1% of the rms speed (isotropic distribution of speeds).
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In kinetic theory of gases, the mean free path is the average distance traveled by a molecule, or a number of molecules per volume, before they make their first collision.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Let $\sigma$ be the collision cross section of one molecule colliding with another.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] As in the previous section, the number density n is defined as the number of molecules per (extensive) volume, or $n=N/V$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Notice that the unit of the collision cross section per volume $n\sigma$ is reciprocal of length.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The kinetic theory of gases deals not only with gases in thermodynamic equilibrium, but also very importantly with gases not in thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This means using Kinetic Theory to consider what are known as "transport properties", such as viscosity, thermal conductivity, mass diffusivity and thermal diffusion.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In its most basic form, kinetic gas theory is only applicable to dilute gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The extension of kinetic gas theory to dense gas mixtures, Revised Enskog Theory, was developed in 1983–1987 by E.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Lòpez de Haro, building on work by H. van Beijeren and M.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In books on elementary kinetic theory one can find results for dilute gas modeling that are used in many fields.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Derivation of the kinetic model for shear viscosity usually starts by considering a Couette flow where two parallel plates are separated by a gas layer.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The upper plate is moving at a constant velocity to the right due to a force *F*.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The lower plate is stationary, and an equal and opposite force must therefore be acting on it to keep it at rest.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The molecules in the gas layer have a forward velocity component u which increase uniformly with distance y above the lower plate.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The non-equilibrium flow is superimposed on a Maxwell-Boltzmann equilibrium distribution of molecular motions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Inside a dilute gas in a Couette flow setup, let $u_{0}$ be the forward velocity of the gas at a horizontal flat layer (labeled as $y=0$ ); $u_{0}$ is along the horizontal direction.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] These molecules made their last collision at $y=\pm \ell \cos \theta$ , where $\ell$ is the mean free path.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Each molecule will contribute a forward momentum of $p_{x}^{\pm }=m\left(u_{0}\pm \ell \cos \theta {\frac {du}{dy}}\right),$ where plus sign applies to molecules from above, and minus sign below.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the forward velocity gradient $du/dy$ can be considered to be constant over a distance of mean free path.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution gives the average (equilibrium) molecular speed as ${\bar {v}}={\frac {2}{\sqrt {\pi }}}v_{p}=2{\sqrt {{\frac {2}{\pi }}{\frac {k_{\mathrm {B} }T}{m}}}}$ where $v_{p}$ is the most probable speed.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] and insert the velocity in the viscosity equation above.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The equation above presupposes that the gas density is low (i.e. the pressure is low).
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] This implies that the transport of momentum through the gas due to the translational motion of molecules is much larger than the transport due to momentum being transferred between molecules during collisions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The transfer of momentum between molecules is explicitly accounted for in Revised Enskog theory, which relaxes the requirement of a gas being dilute.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The viscosity equation further presupposes that there is only one type of gas molecules, and that the gas molecules are perfect elastic and hard core particles of spherical shape.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The radius r is called collision cross section radius or kinetic radius, and the diameter d is called collision cross section diameter or kinetic diameter of a molecule in a monomolecular gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] There are no simple general relation between the collision cross section and the hard core size of the (fairly spherical) molecule.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The relation depends on shape of the potential energy of the molecule.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] For a real spherical molecule (i.e. a noble gas atom or a reasonably spherical molecule) the interaction potential is more like the Lennard-Jones potential or Morse potential which have a negative part that attracts the other molecule from distances longer than the hard core radius.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The radius for zero Lennard-Jones potential may then be used as a rough estimate for the kinetic radius.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] However, using this estimate will typically lead to an erroneous temperature dependency of the viscosity.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] For such interaction potentials, significantly more accurate results are obtained by numerical evaluation of the required collision integrals.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Consider two parallel plates separated by a gas layer.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Both plates have uniform temperatures, and are so massive compared to the gas layer that they can be treated as thermal reservoirs.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The upper plate has a higher temperature than the lower plate.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The molecules in the gas layer have a molecular kinetic energy $\varepsilon$ which increases uniformly with distance y above the lower plate.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The non-equilibrium energy flow is superimposed on a Maxwell-Boltzmann equilibrium distribution of molecular motions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Let $\varepsilon _{0}$ be the molecular kinetic energy of the gas at an imaginary horizontal surface inside the gas layer.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Again, plus sign applies to molecules from above, and minus sign below.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the temperature gradient $dT/dy$ can be considered to be constant over a distance of mean free path.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the energy transfer from above is in the $-y$ direction, and therefore the overall minus sign in the equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Consider a steady diffusion between two regions of the same gas with perfectly flat and parallel boundaries separated by a layer of the same gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Both regions have uniform number densities, but the upper region has a higher number density than the lower region.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] In the steady state, the number density at any point is constant (that is, independent of time).
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] However, the number density n in the layer increases uniformly with distance y above the lower plate.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The non-equilibrium molecular flow is superimposed on a Maxwell–Boltzmann equilibrium distribution of molecular motions.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Let $n_{0}$ be the number density of the gas at an imaginary horizontal surface inside the layer.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the number density gradient $dn/dy$ can be considered to be constant over a distance of mean free path.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the molecular transfer from above is in the $-y$ direction, and therefore the overall minus sign in the equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The corresponding expression obtained from Revised Enskog Theory may be written as $D=\alpha _{D}D_{0}$ where $\alpha _{D}$ is a factor that tends to unity in the limit of infinite dilution, which accounts for excluded volume and the variation chemical potentials with density.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] The kinetic theory of gases entails that due to the microscopic reversibility of the gas particles' detailed dynamics, the system must obey the principle of detailed balance.
[src:kinetic-theory/kinetic-theory-of-gases] Note that the mobility *μ* = *v*d/*F* can be calculated based on the viscosity of the gas; Therefore, the Einstein–Smoluchowski equation also provides a relation between the mass diffusivity and the viscosity of the gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] In physics (in particular in statistical mechanics), the **Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution**, or **Maxwell(ian) distribution**, is a particular probability distribution named after James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The term "particle" in this context refers to gaseous particles only (atoms or molecules), and the system of particles is assumed to have reached thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The energies of such particles follow what is known as Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics, and the statistical distribution of speeds is derived by equating particle energies with kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Mathematically, the Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution is the chi distribution with three degrees of freedom (the components of the velocity vector in Euclidean space), with a scale parameter measuring speeds in units proportional to the square root of $T/m$ (the ratio of temperature and particle mass).
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution is a result of the kinetic theory of gases, which provides a simplified explanation of many fundamental gaseous properties, including pressure and diffusion.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution applies fundamentally to particle velocities in three dimensions, but turns out to depend only on the speed (the magnitude of the velocity) of the particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] A particle speed probability distribution indicates which speeds are more likely: a randomly chosen particle will have a speed selected randomly from the distribution, and is more likely to be within one range of speeds than another.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The kinetic theory of gases applies to the classical ideal gas, which is an idealization of real gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] In real gases, there are various effects (e.g., van der Waals interactions, vortical flow, relativistic speed limits, and quantum exchange interactions) that can make their speed distribution different from the Maxwell–Boltzmann form.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] However, rarefied gases at ordinary temperatures behave very nearly like an ideal gas and the Maxwell speed distribution is an excellent approximation for such gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This is also true for ideal plasmas, which are ionized gases of sufficiently low density.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The distribution was first derived by Maxwell in 1860 on heuristic grounds.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Boltzmann later, in the 1870s, carried out significant investigations into the physical origins of this distribution.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The distribution can be derived on the ground that it maximizes the entropy of the system.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This probability density function gives the probability, per unit speed, of finding the particle with a speed near v.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This distribution is used for describing systems in equilibrium.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] However, most systems do not start out in their equilibrium state.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The evolution of a system towards its equilibrium state is governed by the Boltzmann equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The equation predicts that for short range interactions, the equilibrium velocity distribution will follow a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] To the right is a molecular dynamics (MD) simulation in which 900 hard sphere particles are constrained to move in a rectangle.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] They interact via perfectly elastic collisions.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The system is initialized out of equilibrium, but the velocity distribution (in blue) quickly converges to the 2D Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution (in orange).
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The mean speed $\langle v\rangle$ , most probable speed (mode) *v*p, and root-mean-square speed ${\textstyle {\sqrt {\langle v^{2}\rangle }}}$ can be obtained from properties of the Maxwell distribution.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This works well for nearly ideal, monatomic gases like helium, but also for molecular gases like diatomic oxygen.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This is because despite the larger heat capacity (larger internal energy at the same temperature) due to their larger number of degrees of freedom, their translational kinetic energy (and thus their speed) is unchanged.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution assumes that the velocities of individual particles are much less than the speed of light, i.e. that $T\ll {\frac {mc^{2}}{k_{\text{B}}}}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] For electrons, the temperature of electrons must be $T_{e}\ll 5.93\times 10^{9}~\mathrm {K}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] For distribution of speeds of relativistic particles, see Maxwell–Jüttner distribution.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] After Maxwell, Ludwig Boltzmann in 1872 also derived the distribution on mechanical grounds and argued that gases should over time tend toward this distribution, due to collisions (see H-theorem).
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] He later (1877) derived the distribution again under the framework of statistical thermodynamics.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The derivations in this section are along the lines of Boltzmann's 1877 derivation, starting with a result known as Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics (from statistical thermodynamics).
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Maxwell–Boltzmann statistics gives the average number of particles found in a given single-particle microstate.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Additionally, the particles are assumed to be in thermal equilibrium.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The denominator in **equation 1** is a normalizing factor so that the ratios $N_{i}:N$ add up to unity — in other words it is a kind of partition function (for the single-particle system, not the usual partition function of the entire system).
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Because velocity and speed are related to energy, Equation (**1**) can be used to derive relationships between temperature and the speeds of gas particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] All that is needed is to discover the density of microstates in energy, which is determined by dividing up momentum space into equal sized regions.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The potential energy is taken to be zero, so that all energy is in the form of kinetic energy.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] where *p*2 is the square of the momentum vector **p** = [*px*, *py*, *pz*].
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The normalizing constant can be determined by recognizing that the probability of a molecule having *some* momentum must be 1.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The distribution is seen to be the product of three independent normally distributed variables $p_{x}$ , $p_{y}$ , and $p_{z}$ , with variance $mk_{\text{B}}T$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Additionally, it can be seen that the magnitude of momentum will be distributed as a Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution, with ${\textstyle a={\sqrt {mk_{\text{B}}T}}}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for the momentum (or equally for the velocities) can be obtained more fundamentally using the H-theorem at equilibrium within the Kinetic theory of gases framework.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] where $d^{3}\mathbf {p}$ is the infinitesimal phase-space volume of momenta corresponding to the energy interval dE.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] At equilibrium, this distribution will hold true for any number of degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] For example, if the particles are rigid mass dipoles of fixed dipole moment, they will have three translational degrees of freedom and two additional rotational degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The energy in each degree of freedom will be described according to the above chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom, and the total energy will be distributed according to a chi-squared distribution with five degrees of freedom.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] This has implications in the theory of the specific heat of a gas.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] which is the Maxwell–Boltzmann velocity distribution.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Like the momentum, this distribution is seen to be the product of three independent normally distributed variables $v_{x}$ , $v_{y}$ , and $v_{z}$ , but with variance ${\textstyle k_{\text{B}}T/m}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] A notable property of the distribution for the velocity vector is direction-independence, which means that velocity components are normally distributed in any selected direction, not only in three base directions x , y , and z .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The Maxwell–Boltzmann distribution for the speed follows immediately from the distribution of the velocity vector, above.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Note that the speed is $v={\sqrt {v_{x}^{2}+v_{y}^{2}+v_{z}^{2}}}$ and the volume element in spherical coordinates $dv_{x}\,dv_{y}\,dv_{z}=v^{2}\sin \theta \,dv\,d\theta \,d\phi =v^{2}\,dv\,d\Omega$ where $\phi$ and $\theta$ are the spherical coordinate angles of the velocity vector.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] Integration of the probability density function of the velocity over the solid angles $d\Omega$ yields an additional factor of $4\pi$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] The derivations show that the validity of the Maxwell–Boltzmann velocity distribution is limited to ideal gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/maxwell-boltzmann-distribution] A generalization of the formula to all gases (ideal and real alike) is known, its derivation starts from the fact that the properties of both ideal and real gases must be independent of the direction.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Imagine a beam of particles being shot through a target, and consider an infinitesimally thin slab of the target (see the figure).
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The atoms (or particles) that might stop a beam particle are shown in red.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The magnitude of the mean free path depends on the characteristics of the system.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where ℓ is the mean free path, n is the number of target particles per unit volume, and σ is the effective cross-sectional area for collision per target particle.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The area of the slab is *L*2, and its volume is *L*2 *dx*.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The typical number of stopping atoms in the slab is the concentration n times the volume, i.e., *n L*2 *dx*.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where σ is the cross-sectional area (or, more formally, the "scattering cross-section") of one atom.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The fraction of particles that are not stopped (attenuated) by the slab is called the transmission $T=I/I_{0}=e^{-x/\ell }$ , where x is equal to the thickness of the slab.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In the kinetic theory of gases, the *mean free path* of a particle, such as a molecule, is the average distance the particle travels between collisions with other moving particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The derivation above assumed the target particles to be at rest; therefore, in reality, the formula $\ell =(n\sigma )^{-1}$ holds for a beam particle with a high speed v relative to the velocities of an ensemble of identical particles with random locations.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In that case, the motions of target particles are comparatively negligible, hence the relative velocity $v_{\text{rel}}\approx v$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] This means that the number of collisions is ${\sqrt {2}}$ times the number with stationary targets.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where $k_{\text{B}}$ is the Boltzmann constant, p is the pressure of the gas and T is the absolute temperature.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In practice, the diameter of gas molecules is not well defined.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In fact, the kinetic diameter of a molecule is defined in terms of the mean free path.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Typically, gas molecules do not behave like hard spheres, but rather attract each other at larger distances and repel each other at shorter distances, as can be described with a Lennard-Jones potential.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] One way to deal with such "soft" molecules is to use the Lennard-Jones σ parameter as the diameter.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Another way is to assume a hard-sphere gas that has the same viscosity as the actual gas being considered.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where m is the molecular mass, $\rho =mp/(k_{\text{B}}T)$ is the density of ideal gas, and *μ* is the dynamic viscosity.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] with $R_{\text{specific}}=k_{\text{B}}/m$ being the specific gas constant, equal to 287 J/(kg.K) for air.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Viscosity *μ* is low, 18.5 μPa·s at (25 °C, 1 bar), and p-dependent.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The following table lists some typical values for air at different pressures at room temperature.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Note that different definitions of the molecular diameter, as well as different assumptions about the value of atmospheric pressure (100 vs 101.3 kPa) and room temperature (293.15 vs 296.15 K (20-23 °C) or even 300 K) can lead to slightly different values of the mean free path.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In gamma-ray radiography the *mean free path* of a pencil beam of mono-energetic photons is the average distance a photon travels between collisions with atoms of the target material.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where *μ* is the linear attenuation coefficient, *μ/ρ* is the mass attenuation coefficient and *ρ* is the density of the material.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The mass attenuation coefficient can be looked up or calculated for any material and energy combination using the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) databases.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In X-ray radiography the calculation of the *mean free path* is more complicated, because photons are not mono-energetic, but have some distribution of energies called a spectrum.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] As photons move through the target material, they are attenuated with probabilities depending on their energy, as a result their distribution changes in process called spectrum hardening.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Because of spectrum hardening, the *mean free path* of the X-ray spectrum changes with distance.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Sometimes one measures the thickness of a material in the *number of mean free paths*.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Material with the thickness of one *mean free path* will attenuate to 37% (1/*e*) of photons.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] This concept is closely related to half-value layer (HVL): a material with a thickness of one HVL will attenuate 50% of photons.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] A standard x-ray image is a transmission image, an image with negative logarithm of its intensities is sometimes called a *number of mean free paths* image.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where *q* is the charge, $\tau$ is the mean free time, *m** is the effective mass, and *v*F is the Fermi velocity of the charge carrier.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] The Fermi velocity can easily be derived from the Fermi energy via the non-relativistic kinetic energy equation.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In thin films, however, the film thickness can be smaller than the predicted mean free path, making surface scattering much more noticeable, effectively increasing the resistivity.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Electron mobility through a medium with dimensions smaller than the mean free path of electrons occurs through ballistic conduction or ballistic transport.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In such scenarios electrons alter their motion only in collisions with conductor walls.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where *Q*s is the scattering efficiency factor.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] *Q*s can be evaluated numerically for spherical particles using Mie theory.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] where *V* is the volume of the cavity, *S* is the total inside surface area of the cavity, and *F* is a constant related to the shape of the cavity.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] For most simple cavity shapes, *F* is approximately 4.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] This relation is used in the derivation of the Sabine equation in acoustics, using a geometrical approximation of sound propagation.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In particle physics the concept of the mean free path is not commonly used, being replaced by the similar concept of attenuation length.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] In particular, for high-energy photons, which mostly interact by electron–positron pair production, the radiation length is used much like the mean free path in radiography.
[src:kinetic-theory/mean-free-path] Independent-particle models in nuclear physics require the undisturbed orbiting of nucleons within the nucleus before they interact with other nucleons.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Once the concentrations are equal the molecules continue to move, but since there is no concentration gradient, the process of molecular diffusion has ceased and is instead governed by the process of self-diffusion, originating from the random motion of the molecules.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] The result of diffusion is a gradual mixing of material such that the distribution of molecules is uniform.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Since the molecules are still in motion, but an equilibrium has been established, the result of molecular diffusion is called a "dynamic equilibrium".
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] In a phase with uniform temperature, absent external net forces acting on the particles, the diffusion process will eventually result in complete mixing.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Consider two systems; S1 and S2 at the same temperature and capable of exchanging particles.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] If there is a change in the potential energy of a system; for example μ1>μ2 (μ is Chemical potential) an energy flow will occur from S1 to S2, because nature always prefers low energy and maximum entropy.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Molecular diffusion is typically described mathematically using Fick's laws of diffusion.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Diffusion is of fundamental importance in many disciplines of physics, chemistry, and biology.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Diffusion is part of the transport phenomena.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Of mass transport mechanisms, molecular diffusion is known as a slower one.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] In cell biology, diffusion is a main form of transport for necessary materials such as amino acids within cells.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Diffusion of solvents, such as water, through a semipermeable membrane is classified as osmosis.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Metabolism and respiration rely in part upon diffusion in addition to bulk or active processes.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] For example, in the alveoli of mammalian lungs, due to differences in partial pressures across the alveolar-capillary membrane, oxygen diffuses into the blood and carbon dioxide diffuses out.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Lungs contain a large surface area to facilitate this gas exchange process.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] The diffusion coefficients for these two types of diffusion are generally different because the diffusion coefficient for chemical diffusion is binary and it includes the effects due to the correlation of the movement of the different diffusing species.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Because chemical diffusion is a net transport process, the system in which it takes place is not an equilibrium system (i.e. it is not at rest yet).
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Many results in classical thermodynamics are not easily applied to non-equilibrium systems.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] However, there sometimes occur so-called quasi-steady states, where the diffusion process does not change in time, where classical results may locally apply.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] As the name suggests, this process is a not a true equilibrium since the system is still evolving.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Non-equilibrium fluid systems can be successfully modeled with Landau-Lifshitz fluctuating hydrodynamics.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] In this theoretical framework, diffusion is due to fluctuations whose dimensions range from the molecular scale to the macroscopic scale.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Chemical diffusion increases the entropy of a system, i.e. diffusion is a spontaneous and irreversible process.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Particles can spread out by diffusion, but will not spontaneously re-order themselves (absent changes to the system, assuming no creation of new chemical bonds, and absent external forces acting on the particle).
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] In case of an ideal mix, the particle diffusion equation holds true and the diffusion coefficient *D* the speed of diffusion in the particle diffusion equation is independent of particle concentration.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Transport of material in stagnant fluid or across streamlines of a fluid in a laminar flow occurs by molecular diffusion.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Two adjacent compartments separated by a partition, containing pure gases A or B may be envisaged.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Random movement of all molecules occurs so that after a period molecules are found remote from their original positions.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] If the partition is removed, some molecules of A move towards the region occupied by B, their number depends on the number of molecules at the region considered.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Concurrently, molecules of B diffuse toward regimens formerly occupied by pure A.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Before this point in time, a gradual variation in the concentration of A occurs along an axis, designated x, which joins the original compartments.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] This variation, expressed mathematically as −dCA/dx, where CA is the concentration of A.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] The negative sign arises because the concentration of A decreases as the distance x increases.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Similarly, the variation in the concentration of gas B is −dCB/dx.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] The rate of diffusion of A, NA, depend on concentration gradient and the average velocity with which the molecules of A moves in the x direction.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] where D is the diffusivity of A through B, proportional to the average molecular velocity and, therefore dependent on the temperature and pressure of gases.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] The rate of diffusion NA is usually expressed as the number of moles diffusing across unit area in unit time.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] As with the basic equation of heat transfer, this indicates that the rate of force is directly proportional to the driving force, which is the concentration gradient.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] This basic equation applies to a number of situations.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Restricting discussion exclusively to steady state conditions, in which neither dCA/dx nor dCB/dx change with time, equimolecular counterdiffusion is considered first.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] If no bulk flow occurs in an element of length dx, the rates of diffusion of two ideal gases (of similar molar volume) A and B must be equal and opposite, that is $N_{A}=-N_{B}$ .
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] The partial pressure of A changes by dPA over the distance dx.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Similarly, the partial pressure of B changes dPB.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] where nA is the number of moles of gas *A* in a volume *V*.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] Considering that dPA/dx = −dPB/dx, it therefore proves that DAB = DBA = D.
[src:kinetic-theory/molecular-diffusion] A similar equation may be derived for the counterdiffusion of gas B.
